                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="388.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="By mastering the fundamentals of visual storytelling, students can turn simple drawings into engaging narratives. They'll learn how to build characters, place them in dynamic scenes, and guide the viewer’s eye using layout and visual flow. This chapter develops both creative thinking and technical drawing skills, giving students the tools to tell powerful stories through pictures." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Label layoutX="55.0" layoutY="110.0" prefHeight="53.0" prefWidth="771.0" text="Chapter 3: Elements of Visual Storytelling">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI Semibold" size="25.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="655.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Good character design shows personality even without words. Factors like age, size, clothing, posture, and style help define who a character is. A knight in rusty armor tells a different story than one in shining gold. Even simple traits like a crooked smile or a slouch can suggest a lot about a character's background or attitude." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="793.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Facial expressions help convey the emotions of a scene—whether it’s joy, fear, surprise, anger, or sadness. Learning to exaggerate and simplify expressions makes them easier to read, especially in cartoons and comics. For example, wide eyes and an open mouth show shock, while narrowed eyes and a frown show anger or suspicion." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="932.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="A character’s movement and posture tell just as much as their face. A person standing tall with hands on hips looks confident, while someone slouched with arms crossed might seem insecure or upset. Practicing gesture drawing helps students create more dynamic, believable characters." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="1049.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="The setting is the world where your story takes place. It gives context to the characters and sets the tone of the scene—whether it's a haunted forest, a busy street, or a quiet bedroom." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="1484.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="3.3 Visual Narrative and Sequencing" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="1523.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Visual storytelling is often about more than just a single image—it’s about a sequence of moments. Sequencing lets artists show progression, action, and change." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="55.0" layoutY="1585.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Storyboards and Panels" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="505.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="3.2 Characters and Expression" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
